commText: Jaiswal and Buttler are at the crease. Jaiswal is on strike. Kwena Maphaka will open the attack
Kwena Maphaka to Jaiswal, no run, short of a good length and well wide of off, Jaiswal saw the width and went hard on the cut, beaten on the top-edge
Kwena Maphaka to Jaiswal, 2 runs, nicely played, short of a good length and just outside off, punched into the gap left of cover-point and Jaiswal is off the mark with a couple
Kwena Maphaka to Jaiswal, no run, much better from Maphaka - full and shaping away from wide of off, lures Jaiswal into a big drive and beats him on the outside edge
Kwena Maphaka to Jaiswal, FOUR, slapped, hint of width wide of off - Jaiswal stays on the back-foot and then drills the drive over cover-point, bounces away to the ropes in a flash

Kwena Maphaka to Jaiswal, FOUR, he's in a hurry - back of a length and angling into the left-hander, Jaiswal was cramped for space on the pull, but he went through with the shot and gets enough to clear mid-on, bounces away to the ropes
Kwena Maphaka to Jaiswal, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Kwena Maphaka to Jaiswal, out Caught by Tim David!! Maiden IPL wicket for Maphaka - rush of blood and that has cost Jaiswal dear - on a good length and just outside off, it wasn't full enough for the drive, Jaiswal's feet didn't go anywhere as he threw his hands on the shot, chipped it uppishly and into the hands of David at cover. MI needed something to go their way and young Maphaka has given them a good start. Jaiswal c Tim David b Kwena Maphaka 10(6) [4s-2]
Bumrahj will take the new ball, a slip in place
Sanju Samson, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Jasprit Bumrah, right-arm fast, comes into the attack
Bumrah to Buttler, wide, on a good length and sliding down leg, Buttler was shaping for the flick and missed, on the bounce to the keeper and it's called as a wide
RR's opening stand this IPL 13(12) vs LSG 9(11) vs DC 10(6) vs MI

Bumrah to Buttler, leg byes, 1 run, short of a good length and jagging back sharply into the right-hander, past Buttler's inside edge and rolled off the pad, behind square on the off-side for a single
Jos Buttler vs MI in IPL (before today) Inns: 8 Runs: 485 Avg: 69.28 SR: 152.03 100s/50s: 1/4 HS: 100

Bumrah to Samson, no run, beauty, short of a good length and just outside off - angles back into the right-hander and then straightens past Samson's edge, he was opened up and he's lucky not to have edged it
Bumrah to Samson, no run, this is an excellent start from Bumrah - short of a good length and shaped away from the right-hander, brings out a timid poke and Samson is beaten on the edge once again
Bumrah to Samson, 5 wides, Bumrah goes for the big inswinger and spills it well down leg, kept swinging and gives Kishan no chance, runs away to the ropes for bonus wides
Bumrah to Samson, no run, short of a good length and angling across the right-hander, Samson watches it closely, lifts his bat and lets it go
Bumrah to Samson, no run, on a good length and just outside off, dabbed with an open face to backward point
Bumrah to Samson, no run, tad fuller and at the stumps, defended back at the bowler
Kwena Maphaka to Buttler, no run, on a good length and pushed across the right-hander, Buttler pokes away from his body and is beaten by the angle - this is a good start from the MI new-ball bowlers
Kwena Maphaka to Buttler, FOUR, nicely played, tad too full from Maphaka - Buttler presses half-forward and jams the drive wide of cover, the timing is sublime and the ball races away to the ropes

Kwena Maphaka to Buttler, 1 run, tad too straight now, on the pads and it's flicked past square leg - the fielder got a hand on the dive and the ball slowed down near the ropes, Buttler's restricted to a single
Kwena Maphaka to Samson, no run, half-an-appeal for LBW, but Samson was struck high on the pads, was the nip-backer and he was beaten on the inside edge as he hopped across
Kwena Maphaka to Samson, FOUR, cracking shot, back of a length and well wide of off - Samson stands tall and then cuts it square past point, no need to run for those
Kwena Maphaka to Samson, FOUR, back-to-back boundaries for Samson and he's away - width on offer and he caresses the cut square past point, 13 off the over

Bumrah to Buttler, FOUR, the boundaries are starting to flow now - overpitched and at the pads, Buttler gets inside the line and then clips it wide of mid-wicket, beat the fielder in the ring and raced away
Bumrah to Buttler, no run, that's loose from Buttler - short of a good length and well wide of off, he went sparring at that and is beaten on the waft

Bumrah to Buttler, no run, that would've been a screamer, but the ball popped out as Hardik hit the ground, full and wide of off - Buttler drilled the drive to the left of mid-off, Hardik swiftly moved to his left and got both hands, but he wasn't in control and let the ball pop out. Went low and to his left, he did well to get to the ball, but couldn't hold on
Bumrah to Buttler, wide, short of a good length and seaming away from wide of off, past the tramlines and is called as a wide

Bumrah to Buttler, no run, the inswinger and that's a good leave from Buttler - trusted the bounce on this wicket, lifts his bat and lets it go. Seamed back in from a length and zipped over the top of off and middle - Ishan Kishan had to dive across to prevent byes
Bumrah to Buttler, 1 run, on a length and angling into the right-hander, tucked past square leg for a single
Bumrah to Samson, wide, fuller length delivery and well wide of off, close to the tramlines and it's deemed as a wide
Bumrah to Samson, FOUR, edged, but the ball runs through the vacant second slip region and runs away to the ropes - was pushed with hard hands from Samson, a genuine edge and he gets away
Akash Madhwal, right-arm fast medium, comes into the attack
Akash Madhwal to Buttler, 1 run, on a good length and shaping back into the right-hander, nudged wide of mid-on for a single
Akash Madhwal to Samson, THATS OUT!! Bowled!!

Akash Madhwal to Samson, out Bowled!! Chopped on! Madhwal has this happy knack of taking wickets and he's struck with his 2nd ball of the season - short and wide of off, Samson lazily threw his hands on the drive, the feet hardly moved and the thick inside edge clattered into his off-stump. MI keeping themselves in the hunt with timely wickets. Samson b Akash Madhwal 12(10) [4s-3]
Riyan Parag, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Akash Madhwal to Riyan Parag, 1 run, length ball on the pads, tucked through square leg for a single
Akash Madhwal to Buttler, no run, on a good length and in that channel just outside off - Buttler shuffles across on the nudge, closes the bat-face and gets a soft edge to the off-side
Akash Madhwal to Buttler, wide, full and wide of off, well past the tramlines and is called as a wide
Akash Madhwal to Buttler, no run, short and well wide of off, Buttler swings across the line and is beaten by the angle
Akash Madhwal to Buttler, no run, back of a length and well wide of off, Buttler rides the bounce and pushes it to the off-side

Over Summary (1-5) -> Jaiswal hits back-to-back boundaries, but Maphaka gets his wicket -> Bumrah bowls a wayward delivery down the leg-side, five wides -> Samson opens his account with a cracking boundary through point -> Hardik puts down Buttler's tough catch at mid-off -> Madhwal strikes in his first over, Samson is bowled
A third for Bumrah on the trot. Can he strike now?
Bumrah to Riyan Parag, 1 run, leading edge!! Full and angles in sharply onto the pads. Parag tried to close the bat face but gets a leading edge on it to goes between the cordon and backward point
Bumrah to Buttler, 1 run, shortens the length and gets it to swing back in towards middle and leg. Buttler with a soft push towards mid-on for a single
Bumrah to Riyan Parag, no run, 137 clicks, good length and angles back sharply towards middle stump. A solid forward defence from Riyan Parag
Bumrah to Riyan Parag, no run, full and a hint of outswing on this one, leaves the batter from off stump. Blocked towards covers
Bumrah to Riyan Parag, no run, yorker length delivery on off, driven through covers but Pandya makes a superb diving stop. Gets the applause from his teammates for that one!

Bumrah to Riyan Parag, no run, Bumrah goes shorter and just outside off. Parag arches his back to get out of harm's way. Powerplay comes to an end, RR have done well to ensure Bumrah ends this spell wicketless.
Akash Madhwal to Buttler, 1 run, good length onto off stump, gets a thickish inside edge to the right of mid-on
Akash Madhwal to Riyan Parag, 1 run, on a length and gets a bit of extra bounce. Parag defends off his splice towards sweeper cover
Akash Madhwal to Buttler, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Akash Madhwal to Buttler, out Caught by Chawla!! Game on!! A short ball from Madhwal and Buttler couldn't resist himself. Top-edges the pull slightly and it goes straight down the throat of Chawla at fine leg. The fielder didn't have to move an inch. and makes no mistake. Buttler's poor start to the IPL continues, Mumbai are fighting back in this one! Buttler c Chawla b Akash Madhwal 13(16) [4s-2]
Ravichandran Ashwin, right handed bat, comes to the crease
Akash Madhwal to Ashwin, no run, on a length and slightly wider. Pushed towards covers
A second game where Ashwin has got a batting promotion.
Akash Madhwal to Ashwin, 1 run, on a length and slightly wider, Ashwin with a very confident punch from his crease towards deep extra cover
Akash Madhwal to Riyan Parag, 1 run, fuller with a much straighter line, driven down to long-on
Gerald Coetzee, right-arm fast, comes into the attack
Gerald Coetzee to Riyan Parag, no run, fraction short of length and keeps it tight on off stump. Parag taps it into the ground towards backward point
Buttler's last six IPL innings: 0(3) vs KKR 0(2) vs RCB 0(4) vs PBKS 11(9) vs LSG 11(16) vs DC 13(16) vs MI - today

Gerald Coetzee to Riyan Parag, FOUR, hits that hard length onto off stump again, Parag was ready expected that kind of delivery and just crouches low and hangs out his bat. Guides it off the sticker over the slip fielder for a boundary. The shot of a confident man!

Gerald Coetzee to Riyan Parag, FOUR, short of length and straying a bit too straight. Parag doesn't miss out as he pulls it very fine. Using the pace of the bowler, the ball races away towards the boundary before the fielder could react
Gerald Coetzee to Riyan Parag, no run, Coetzee goes fuller on middle and leg, defended by Parag
Gerald Coetzee to Riyan Parag, leg byes, 1 run, 140.1 clicks, skiddy, fullish delivery onto the pads, tickled towards fine leg
Gerald Coetzee to Ashwin, 1 run, back of length and near the ribs, Ashwin with a slight inward movement tucks it towards deep backward square leg

Time-out. Despite the three wickets, Rajasthan in control of this game at the moment. Riyan Parag has started brightly after last game's man of the match performance, and Ashwin's experience at the other end should do the team well. Mumbai need to keep the wickets coming to have any chance. The good news is they aren't ready to throw the towel yet for sure, let's see how the game proceeds...
Akash Madhwal to Ashwin, 1 run, fuller delivery that skids onto middle and leg. Ashwin closes the bat face to the right of mid-on for a single
Akash Madhwal to Riyan Parag, 1 run, good length onto the thigh pad, turned towards deep mid-wicket
Akash Madhwal to Ashwin, 1 run, good length and offering width, Ashwin punches it uppishly but to the right of backward point. Stopped by sweeper cover, just a single
Akash Madhwal to Riyan Parag, 1 run, length ball on the pads, easily clipped towads deep mid-wicket

Akash Madhwal to Ashwin, byes, 2 runs, I0$ A length ball outside off, keeps a tad low and catches an underedge off the bottom of the bat as Ashwin tried to punch it away. Bounces one and deflects off the boots of Kishan for a couple of runs
Akash Madhwal to Ashwin, 2 runs, back of length and wider, Ashwin gets closer and plays a confident backfoot punch in front of square. Ends the over with another couple
First over of spin. Chahal was very successful earlier on, let's see how Chawla gets along
Piyush Chawla, right-arm leg break, comes into the attack
Chawla to Riyan Parag, 1 run, a flat delivery at the stumps, Parag stays back and tucks it to deep mid-wicket
Chawla to Ashwin, 1 run, tossed fuller onto off, Ashwin with a big stride forwards pushes it out to long-off
Shouts of 'Rohit, Rohit' from the fans
Chawla to Riyan Parag, no run, flat delivery onto off stump, punched towards Pandya at covers. A few 'boos' break out in the crowd as the captain stops the ball
Chawla to Riyan Parag, 1 run, googly from Chawla, Parag waits for the spin and tucks it to square leg
Chawla to Ashwin, 2 runs, flighted up outside off, Ashwin drives it square for a couple of runs
Chawla to Ashwin, no run, ends with another googly, comes in towards off stump. Ashwin cuts it from the stumps towards the point fielder who gets low on the dive to stop the single

Over summary (6-10) -> Bumrah concedes only two runs in the 6th over -> Buttler perishes, Madhwal gets him with a short ball -> Ashwin promoted, walks out to bat at number 5 -> Parag hits back-to-back boundaries against Coetzee -> A steady partnership building between Ashwin and Parag
Still no sign of Hardik the bowler, Coetzee to continue
Gerald Coetzee [1.0-0-9-0] is back into the attack
Gerald Coetzee to Riyan Parag, no run, superb yorker from Coetzee. Dug out to the left of the bowler
Gerald Coetzee to Riyan Parag, FOUR, I0$ A fuller delivery just outside off, was pretty quick. Parag so early to judge the length and chips it over covers from his crease with minimal foot movement
Gerald Coetzee to Riyan Parag, no run, on a length and straighter, angling inwards. Parag tried to pull it away but it goes under his bat and he cops a blow on his stomach
Gerald Coetzee to Riyan Parag, 1 run, good length and a bit wide, punched towards sweeper cover
Gerald Coetzee to Ashwin, 2 runs, on a length and even wider, Ashwin plays it late and punches it behind square to pick up another couple of runs
Gerald Coetzee to Ashwin, FOUR, streaky!! back of length delivery angling inwards, Ashwin tried a swivel pull and gets an inside edge that goes past the stumps and towards the fine leg boundary
Chawla to Riyan Parag, 1 run, on a length, leg spinner. Parag stays in his crease and punches it down to long-off
Chawla to Ashwin, no run, pushed fuller and quicker outside off. Ashwin went for a big drive away but can't connect
Chawla to Ashwin, no run, pushed fuller and was the googly, Ashwin with his big forward stride drives it back to Chawla
Chawla to Ashwin, 1 run, length ball just outside off, Ashwin cuts it square of the wicket for a single
Chawla to Riyan Parag, no run, pushed fuller outside off and spins away, beats the bat as Parag tried to drive through covers
Chawla to Riyan Parag, 1 run, full on leg stump, Parag makes room for himself to squeeze the drive down to long-off
Akash Madhwal [3.0-0-13-2] is back into the attack
Akash Madhwal to Riyan Parag, 1 run, fuller skiddy delivery outside off, catches the edge as Parag went for the drive. Goes towards square third-man
Akash Madhwal to Ashwin, THATS OUT!! Caught!!

Akash Madhwal to Ashwin, out Caught by Tilak Varma!! MI needed that breakthrough and once again it is Madhwal who provides it! The skiddy nature of his bowling causes the downfall of Ashwin as he tries to play cross batted to this length ball on off stump. Gets a flying edge as he was slightly late on it. Lobs it behind backward point where Varma runs back to take a well judged catch. Ashwin c Tilak Varma b Akash Madhwal 16(16) [4s-1]
The RR impact sub Shubham Dubey comes on.
Shubham Dubey, left handed bat, comes to the crease
Akash Madhwal to Shubham Dubey, 1 run, length ball angling inwards from round the wicket to the left-hander. Tucked towards the left of mid-on for a single
Akash Madhwal to Riyan Parag, no run, wide yorker from Madhwal. Stabbed towards backward point
Akash Madhwal to Riyan Parag, 1 run, on a length and straight, punched down to long-on

Akash Madhwal to Shubham Dubey, FOUR, cracking shot!! On a length delivery outside off, Dubey with a confident punch that runs away between covers and mid-off. The fielders stood still as the southpaw from Vidarbha picks up his first IPL boundary
Shubham Dubey in SMAT 2023/24 Inns: 7 Runs: 221 Avg: 73.66 SR: 187.28 HS: 58*
Bumrah to bowl his last. Big over coming up!!
Jasprit Bumrah [3.0-0-19-0] is back into the attack
Bumrah to Riyan Parag, 1 run, back of length and wide, neatly dabbed to the left of backward point for a single
Rohit Sharma moves it to first slip for Dubey
Bumrah to Shubham Dubey, 1 run, angling in from a length onto the pads, flicked towards deep square leg. A couple of bounces to the fielder
Akash Madhwal at Wankhede in IPL Inns: 4 Ovrs: 14 Wkts: 10 Avg: 11.10 SR: 8.4 ER: 7.92 BBI: 4/37
Bumrah to Riyan Parag, no run, short of length outside off, Parag was tempted to ramp it away but retracted his bat at the last moment
Bumrah to Riyan Parag, FOUR, smoked!! A full, quick delivery at the base on off, Parag drills it to the left of mid-off for a boundary. He is a batter playing with sublime confidence at the moment
Bumrah to Riyan Parag, no run, on a length and much straigther from Bumrah. Defended leg side
Bumrah to Riyan Parag, wide, short of length and angling across, angles down the leg side
Bumrah to Riyan Parag, no run, good length delivery onto off stump, a very respectful defence from Riyan Parag. RR see off Bumrah without giving any of their wickets away
Piyush Chawla [2.0-0-8-0] is back into the attack
Chawla to Shubham Dubey, 1 run, tossed up onto off stump, Dubey chips it towards long-off for a single

Chawla to Riyan Parag, SIX, out of here!! Fully in control of this one, clears that front leg and slams it over wide long-on for an 82m maximum. Chawla tosses it onto into the arc for Parag and gets the treatment!!
Chawla to Riyan Parag, 1 run, flatter trajectory on off, Parag stays deep and slaps it to the left of long-off
Chawla to Shubham Dubey, no run, a quick googly outside off, Dubey tried to slog across the line but missed it
Chawla to Shubham Dubey, 1 run, full on the pads, clipped towards square leg
Chawla to Riyan Parag, 1 run, googly onto the pads, Parag tucks it down to deep mid-wicket from his crease

Over summary (11-15) -> Coetzee concedes 11 runs in the 11th over of the chase -> Madhwal bags his third wicket in the form of Ashwin -> Impact player - Shubham Dubey walks out to bat after Ashwin's dismissal -> 100 up for Rajasthan Royals in the 14th over -> Only 15 required off 30 balls
Gerald Coetzee [2.0-0-20-0] is back into the attack

Gerald Coetzee to Riyan Parag, SIX, glorious!! He seems to have some kind of special treatment reserved for South African quicks!! A full delivery outside off, Parag with an effortless hoist on his cover drive that goes all the way. Just an extension of his drive, lofts it in full control and gets it all the way

Gerald Coetzee to Riyan Parag, SIX, back-to-back fifties!! A length ball onto off stump, Parag with a big cross batted slap that isn't timed off the middle but goes beyond deep mid-wicket on these short Wankhede boundaries. What a coming of age season this is turning out to be for the boy from Assam!!

Gerald Coetzee to Riyan Parag, FOUR, banged short at the stumps, Parag goes for a hook and gets a top-edge that flies over the keeper's head for a boundary. That'll be the game for RR, Parag has got them home in a hurry. Third win for Rajasthan, third loss for Mumbai.

22:58 Local Time, 17:28 GMT, 22:58 IST: Rajasthan chase this down on a canter after a bit of stutter in the powerplay. Once again, it is Riyan Parag who has been their star with the bat, he's really turned a new leaf this season. Showing a lot more responsibility, maturity and ability, the 22-year-old boy has taken Rajasthan home with more than 4 overs to spare!! The game however was set up by their bowlers, as Boult struck thrice in the powerplay, and then Chahal and Burger got amongst the wickets to reduce Mumbai to a total of just 125. In reply, Jaiswal's lean start to the season continued, as he chipped one straight to covers. Samson fell cheaply as well, chopping one onto his stumps against Madhwal, who struck again to dismiss Buttler. RR were a bit shacky at 48/3 but last game's dup of Ashwin and Parag stablised the ship and got the visitors home. A spirited bowling effort from Mumbai, but they were always a few runs short on this ground. Stick on for the captain comments...

Hardik Pandya | MI Captain: Yes, a tough night, we didn't start the way we wanted to start. I wanted to counter, we were in a decent position to get us around 150-160, but my wicket allowed them to get back more into the game, I needed to do a lot more. It's okay, we didn't expect such a surface, but you can't always have it as a batter, it's nice at times for the bowlers to have a say. It's all about doing the right things, (correct) results happen at times, at some other times it doesn't. As a group, we believe we can do a lot better, but we need to be a bit more disciplined and show a lot more courage.

Riyan Parag: Nothing has changed, just that I have simplified things. Before I would think about things too much, this year the goal is simple, watch the ball, hit the ball. It's a funny thing, I have said it before, this is the exact situation I go in to bat in domestic cricket. When Jos got out, I went in to bat, this is when I usually go out to bat. For 3-4 years I haven't performed well (in the IPL.) When the performances are not coming, you get back to the drawing board. I practised really hard, I have practised these kind of scenarios. Dad likes to watch everything from home, he likes to analyse everything, but my mom is here.
Since 2023 IPL, six of the eight matches at the Wankhede have been won by the chasing side.
Results in IPL 2024 so far Matches - 14 Home teams won - 12 Away teams won - 2 (KKR vs RCB & RR vs MI)
Riyan Parag in IPL 2024 43(29) vs LSG 84*(45) vs DC 54*(39) vs MI
Most wickets in first 9 IPL matches (Indian) 18 - Sandeep Sharma 17 - Akash Madhwal* 17 - Khaleel Ahmed 16 - Amit Mishra
Hardik Pandya as captain in first 3 matches \nFor GT - W W W \nFor MI - L L L
Stats round-up by Shashikant Singh
Presentations underway and the stadium is virtually empty already. Not often do you see this at the Wankhede, even if MI are on the losing side

Sanju Samson | RR Captain: I think the toss was the game changer. The wicket was too sticky to start off, and the experience of Boult and Burger helped us. He's playing since 10-15 years, and that is what we expected with the new ball. Didn't expect 4-5 wickets to fall, but we knew our bowlers would do well. We know we have big individuals in our team, but where we stand out is everyone recognises their role, does it and moves on. The likes of Ash and Chahal realised we had a good powerplay, and they kept it tight without really looking for wickets. (On Chahal) I think he was really fired up for this IPL, and he's been doing well for the past 2-3 years for us.

Trent Boult | Player of the Match: (On first over wickets) Never a certainity in this format, but happy to fill my role and take wickets with the new ball. We won the toss, did what we spoke about, got a couple of wickets and put the pressure on the batters. (On Rohit Sharma wicket) I've played against him a lot, and it is just about doing something different against him. Doesn't always work this way, but happy when it does. Nandre has been a great find, wears his heart on his chest like a lot of SA bowlers do. Sandy has been doing well, although he missed out today. Ash and Chahal always chip in as well. Good to be part of this bowling unit.

So Rajasthan maintain their 100% record in the IPL. Their investments from the past are all coming good now, particularly Riyan Parag. And their success shows the value of a settled core for a franchise tournament. Things are looking in the ‘pink of health’ for Sanju Samson and co.

How I wish I could say the same about Mumbai Indians. They call themselves ‘One Family’ but at the moment it seems like a family dealing with the bereavement of a dear one, perhaps of competitive cricket. There is a palpable uneasiness and an eerie quietness amongst the team, their fans and the stadium. A stadium that has seen so many magical moments felt today like a place where dreams come to die. The easiest thing for fans to do is to turn on the captain who’s cut a divisive figure, but the mature, more sensible thing would be to get behind him and the team that’s still very much trying and giving it their all in the fight. Food for thought? On that note, time to call it a night on this game, this is I0$ signing off on behalf of I1$ and I2$
